Comment: I've been told that in openings, most of the time it's better not to take if you don't have to, but instead to build preasure on the piece... so was this a good choice?
I think this was a mistake. Once I take the pawn on the b file, white will have to move another piece to defend the knight, or move the knight itself...
A good spot, since I can't immidiately kick his knight, along with the fork threat on the c file.
It was now I noticed that whites king actually isn't that well protected. So I make a sacrifice, for an attack.
He takes, forking my king and rook.
If he retreats now, He'll be down a pawn when I take the knight or bishop.
Instead, he takes the inactive rook.
And I get his active bishop.
I understand his logic here, but he seems to have forgotten his defenses.
